00:04:23.060 --> 00:04:26.450
So, basically, what is it?

00:04:26.450 --> 00:04:27.970
What is the "Song of Songs?"

00:04:27.970 --> 00:04:30.380
It is, simply stated, love poetry.

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:32.710
It is exquisite love poetry.

00:04:32.710 --> 00:04:36.180
And, of course, as we just heard,
is everyone's favorite poem.

00:04:36.180 --> 00:04:37.940
So the immediate question,
of course,

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:40.470
is why is it in the biblical canon?

00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:42.100
How did it get there?

00:04:42.100 --> 00:04:47.360
And the answer is, because texts
have an afterlife, which is to say,

00:04:47.360 --> 00:04:49.640
although the author of the
"Song of Songs," according

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:55.810
to all biblical scholars,
intended it as simply love poetry,

00:04:55.810 --> 00:04:58.250
what Robert Alter calls
and ode to intimacy.

00:04:58.250 --> 00:05:00.400
And I'll come back to
that point in a moment.

00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:02.470
It was later Jews and
later Christians

00:05:02.470 --> 00:05:05.300
who reinterpreted the text
in that text afterlife,

00:05:05.300 --> 00:05:06.770
if I can use that expression.

00:05:06.770 --> 00:05:11.380
For Jews, the "Song of Songs" was
not the love between a young man

00:05:11.380 --> 00:05:14.830
and a young woman, but rather
was the love between God

00:05:14.830 --> 00:05:17.270
and the people of Israel.

00:05:17.270 --> 00:05:20.320
God being masculine; the people
of Israel being feminine.

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:26.100
While Christians saw the
same love, in their case,

00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:28.260
the love between Jesus
and the church.

00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:34.350
Again, masculine and feminine,
as exemplified in the poem.

00:05:34.350 --> 00:05:37.630
The most famous passage from
post-biblical literature

00:05:37.630 --> 00:05:42.300 position:56%
that we can cite in this regard is
the well-known maxim of Rabbi Akiva,

00:05:42.300 --> 00:05:49.090 position:56%
a second-century CE rabbi who played
on the Hebrew words Shir Hashirim

00:05:49.090 --> 00:05:52.390
in Hebrew, "Song of Songs," as a
way of expressing the superlative

00:05:52.390 --> 00:05:53.810
and is grammatically equivalent

00:05:53.810 --> 00:05:57.300
to the expression Kodesh
Kodashim, Holy of Holies.

00:05:57.300 --> 00:06:01.170
And, according to Rabbi Akiva,
the <i>Book of Song of Songs </i>,

00:06:01.170 --> 00:06:04.030
if all the scriptures are
holy, the Book of Song

00:06:04.030 --> 00:06:06.880
of Songs is the Holy of Holies.

00:06:06.880 --> 00:06:11.050
Here's an example from an
Christian art of the expression

00:06:11.050 --> 00:06:12.420
that I have just indicated to you.

00:06:12.420 --> 00:06:15.020
The opening words of the
<i>Book of Song of Songs </i>,

00:06:15.020 --> 00:06:17.380
after the superscription
which introduces the book,

00:06:17.380 --> 00:06:22.150
is the female lover asking
her male lover to "kiss me."

00:06:22.150 --> 00:06:23.600 position:56%
And if you look at your translation,

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:27.500
you can see that in
chapter one, verse two.

00:06:27.500 --> 00:06:31.800 position:56%
This actually comes from The Lothian
Bible, one of the great treasures

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:35.120
of the Pierpont Morgan
Library in New York City.

00:06:35.120 --> 00:06:37.490
And you can see the Latin
words there indicated.

00:06:37.490 --> 00:06:40.740
The text, of course, is in the
Latin, the Vulgated Saint Jerome.

00:06:40.740 --> 00:06:45.260 position:56%
And you can see the Latin words, the
opening words of the "Song of Songs"

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:48.660
in Latin there, osculator
me, kiss me.

00:06:48.660 --> 00:06:52.280
This text was written
in 1220 in England,

00:06:52.280 --> 00:06:53.720
and it's beautifully illuminated.

00:06:53.720 --> 00:06:56.570
And here's just one instance where
you can see the love of the male

00:06:56.570 --> 00:06:59.050
and female, although, in this
case, it's obviously intended

00:06:59.050 --> 00:07:02.270
by the illuminator to
be Jesus and the church.

00:07:02.270 --> 00:07:05.190
I cannot show you Jewish art
showing you the same thing

00:07:05.190 --> 00:07:08.900
because Jews would shy away
from indicating such things.

00:07:08.900 --> 00:07:11.510
But, of course, there is
beautiful Jewish art of The Bible,

00:07:11.510 --> 00:07:13.880
and so I'll leave this
image up for a bit here.

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:16.040
This is the beginning of
the the "Song of Songs"

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:20.250
in the Kennicott Bible,
written in Spain in 1476,

00:07:20.250 --> 00:07:23.240
one of the great testimonies to
that remarkable Jewish community

00:07:23.240 --> 00:07:25.020
of medieval Spain on the eve

00:07:25.020 --> 00:07:28.630
of their expulsion just
16 years later in 1492.

00:07:28.630 --> 00:07:30.850
This Bible has been at
the Bodleian Library

00:07:30.850 --> 00:07:34.430
in Oxford since the 18th century.

00:07:34.430 --> 00:07:37.310
Now let's talk a little
bit about the text.

00:07:37.310 --> 00:07:38.610
And you have the translation.

00:07:38.610 --> 00:07:42.410 position:56%
It was actually produced by myself
and my co-author, and former student

00:07:42.410 --> 00:07:44.620
as well, Scott Nagel of the
University of Washington.

00:07:44.620 --> 00:07:46.520
And he and I wrote
a book on the "Song

00:07:46.520 --> 00:07:48.260
of "Songs" called <i>Solomon's
Vineyard </i>.

00:07:48.260 --> 00:07:51.850
In fact, I've given you the
translation that we produced along

00:07:51.850 --> 00:07:53.610
with some -- two sets of notes.

00:07:53.610 --> 00:07:57.280
One is a set of literary notes and
