00:08:02.170 --> 00:08:03.840
which we're not going to do today.

00:08:03.840 --> 00:08:05.310
But at least you have
the translation

00:08:05.310 --> 00:08:08.960
and the literary notes
at the bottom there.

00:08:08.960 --> 00:08:11.090
Now let's talk about
this issue of intimacy.

00:08:11.090 --> 00:08:13.680
Normally in The Bible
we do not see intimacy.

00:08:13.680 --> 00:08:15.070
We have an occasional scene.

00:08:15.070 --> 00:08:19.060
In the Book of Genesis we
get a quick look at Isaac

00:08:19.060 --> 00:08:21.300
and Rebekah playing
with one another,

00:08:21.300 --> 00:08:24.090
the Hebrew text there [foreign
words], with one another.

00:08:24.090 --> 00:08:25.410
But we see them from a distance.

00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:29.370
We actually see them through
the eyes of Avi-Melech before --

00:08:29.370 --> 00:08:30.700
the King of the Philistines,

00:08:30.700 --> 00:08:35.080
so that we don't really get a
chance to see them up close.

00:08:35.080 --> 00:08:37.910
Or we get to see Jacob and Rachel,
also in the Book of Genesis,

00:08:37.910 --> 00:08:40.740
meeting at the well, and they kiss.

00:08:40.740 --> 00:08:44.500
And we actually are taken into
their marriage bed, if I can say,

00:08:44.500 --> 00:08:47.900
a few verses later in
Genesis Chapter 29.

00:08:47.900 --> 00:08:49.240
But we don't get intimacy.

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:53.900
Each of these scenes is described
in very terse, prosaic manner --

00:08:53.900 --> 00:08:56.350
they did this, they did that.

00:08:56.350 --> 00:08:59.340
Even in the David and
Bathsheba story,

00:08:59.340 --> 00:09:02.700
where one would think one
would maybe see some passion,

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:06.170
all we read there is that
she came into the palace,

00:09:06.170 --> 00:09:08.510
they had intercourse,
and she left --

00:09:08.510 --> 00:09:15.230
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:09:15.230 --> 00:09:19.320
And he took her, and she came
to him and he lay with her

00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:21.520
and she returned to her house.

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:22.820
Was there any wooing?

00:09:22.820 --> 00:09:24.120
Was there any embrace?

00:09:24.120 --> 00:09:25.420
Were there any words spoken?

00:09:25.420 --> 00:09:26.720
Was there any passion?

00:09:26.720 --> 00:09:28.020
Was there any emotion?

00:09:28.020 --> 00:09:29.320
Was there any romance?

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:32.260
None of that is indicated
by the author of 2 Samuel.

00:09:32.260 --> 00:09:36.810
The biblical authors, the prose
authors, just told the basic facts

00:09:36.810 --> 00:09:39.790
in this very laconic
style of writing.

00:09:39.790 --> 00:09:41.900
But "Song of Songs" is poetry.

00:09:41.900 --> 00:09:44.610
Let's just look at one other
instance of the way the <i>Book</i>

00:09:44.610 --> 00:09:47.280
<i>of Song of Songs </i>is
illuminated at the end

00:09:47.280 --> 00:09:50.510
of chapter eight in
the Kennicott Bible.

00:09:50.510 --> 00:09:53.620
And with love poetry, we have
something very, very different.

00:09:53.620 --> 00:09:58.700
Love poetry gives us all of
the sensual aspects of what

00:09:58.700 --> 00:10:01.000
that word love indicates for us.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:02.740
In fact, if you'd look
at your translation,

00:10:02.740 --> 00:10:05.240
just begin with chapter
one, verse two.

00:10:05.240 --> 00:10:07.870
"May he kiss me with
the kisses of his mouth;

00:10:07.870 --> 00:10:10.610
for your love is better than wine."

00:10:10.610 --> 00:10:12.940
Now I'd like to point
out to you here

00:10:12.940 --> 00:10:18.060
that this may sound a little
strange to us in our English sense.

00:10:18.060 --> 00:10:20.470
But this is perfectly
acceptable in Hebrew poetry.

00:10:20.470 --> 00:10:24.660
Do you notice how the A line --
biblical poetry is parallelistic?

00:10:24.660 --> 00:10:27.070
Usually a set of couplets
where the A line

00:10:27.070 --> 00:10:28.620 position:56%
and the B line speak to one another.

00:10:28.620 --> 00:10:32.090
The A lines states the point,
and the B line will enhance it

00:10:32.090 --> 00:10:34.100
or emphasize it in some way.

00:10:34.100 --> 00:10:38.060
Notice that in the A line, he is
addressed in the third person.

00:10:38.060 --> 00:10:40.750
She says, "May he kiss me
with the kisses of his mouth."

00:10:40.750 --> 00:10:42.210
There's a distance there.

00:10:42.210 --> 00:10:44.410
But in the B line, she
shifts to second person.

00:10:44.410 --> 00:10:45.710
She addresses him directly.

00:10:45.710 --> 00:10:48.690 position:56%
"For your love is better than wine."

00:10:48.690 --> 00:10:53.400
And we'll find other examples of
this occurring in the poem as well.

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:56.680
And if you turn ahead, for
example, to other instances.

00:10:56.680 --> 00:11:02.080
In chapter one, verse 12 and
13, she's still speaking.

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:04.920
Her voice is in the italics there.

00:11:04.920 --> 00:11:10.410
"My nard gives forth its scent
sachet of myrrh as my beloved to me

00:11:10.410 --> 00:11:13.150
between my breasts
may he lodge," right?

00:11:13.150 --> 00:11:18.150
A woman's sachet, a little bag
that would contain the fragrance

00:11:18.150 --> 00:11:23.960
which she would use to make her
body attractive is described here

00:11:23.960 --> 00:11:25.260
as between her breasts.

00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:27.650
But she envisions that
her male lover,

00:11:27.650 --> 00:11:31.030
that this is where he will lodge,
He's like the little sachet

00:11:31.030 --> 00:11:33.590
of fragrance that lies
between her breasts.

00:11:33.590 --> 00:11:37.580
So when I talk about
intimacy and sensual poetry,

00:11:37.580 --> 00:11:41.100
this is what you're seeing here
in the <i>Book of Song of Songs </i>.

00:11:41.100 --> 00:11:45.220
Or turn ahead to chapter
two, verse six.

00:11:45.220 --> 00:11:48.270
"His left hand is beneath
my head," she says,

00:11:48.270 --> 00:11:50.880
"and his right hand embraces me."

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:53.560
Didn't such things occur in
all of those prosaic stories

00:11:53.560 --> 00:11:55.740
that are referred to
earlier in biblical scenes?

00:11:55.740 --> 00:11:58.340
And the answer is,
almost undoubtedly yes.

00:11:58.340 --> 00:12:03.340
But, again, it's the prose
writers who deny us those images.

00:12:03.340 --> 00:12:06.000
But it's the writers of
the poetry that allows us

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.840
to see and to hear these texts.

00:12:08.840 --> 00:12:11.850
Now, if you look at
chapter one, verse two --

00:12:11.850 --> 00:12:15.150
here we are again on the image.

00:12:15.150 --> 00:12:19.430
We join the dialog, as
it were, in medias res,

00:12:19.430 --> 00:12:22.030
and actually we'll end
in such fashion as well.

00:12:22.030 --> 00:12:25.530
It's just two lovers on a
stage talking to one another.

00:12:25.530 --> 00:12:27.510
Now we don't get a backstory.

00:12:27.510 --> 00:12:30.870
She just begins with the opening
line that you see there, right?

00:12:30.870 --> 00:12:34.400
She just invites the kisses
between the two lovers.

00:12:34.400 --> 00:12:35.700
Now the two lovers speak

00:12:35.700 --> 00:12:38.360
to each other throughout the
eight chapters of the poem.

00:12:38.360 --> 00:12:40.910
But they are never truly together.

00:12:40.910 --> 00:12:44.550
If I were staging this, and
I'll talk about performance

00:12:44.550 --> 00:12:46.610
in a just moment, if
I were staging this,

00:12:46.610 --> 00:12:50.290
I actually would envision the
female lover standing on one side

00:12:50.290 --> 00:12:53.480
and the male lover standing on
another side, and they would speak

00:12:53.480 --> 00:12:54.840
to one another occasionally.

00:12:54.840 --> 00:12:58.640 position:56%
They would speak to the audience, as
it were, perhaps a group this size,

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:00.970
as they recited the poetry.

00:13:00.970 --> 00:13:03.210
Maybe occasionally
turning to another.

00:13:03.210 --> 00:13:05.620
But the poem unfolds
without us actually getting

00:13:05.620 --> 00:13:07.400
to see the two lovers,
the male lover

00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:09.740
and the female lover,
ever really together.

00:13:09.740 --> 00:13:12.790
And that's true of the opening
line and it's certainly true

00:13:12.790 --> 00:13:17.280
of the last line of the poem which
we'll look at in just a moment.

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:21.260
This shift, by the way, as we just
saw here in chapter one, verse two,

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:24.950
from second person to third
person, also occurs elsewhere.

00:13:24.950 --> 00:13:31.180
Take a look, for example, at
chapter two, verse 16 and verse 17,

00:13:33.950 --> 00:13:39.440
where she says in verse 16, "My
beloved is mine and I am his,

00:13:39.440 --> 00:13:41.160
grazing among the lilies."

00:13:41.160 --> 00:13:42.870 position:56%
Famous passage from "Song of Songs."

00:13:42.870 --> 00:13:45.530
Again she's referring to
