quoting yet a third party, you know,

00:39:08.450 --> 00:39:10.620
author x, whom we don't know.

00:39:10.620 --> 00:39:13.390
So texts were communal property.

00:39:13.390 --> 00:39:17.690 position:56%
What we do know occasionally are the
names of the scribes who actually,

00:39:17.690 --> 00:39:20.640
in ancient colophons, would
even give us their names.

00:39:20.640 --> 00:39:23.220
Nothing like the more
well-developed medieval colophons

00:39:23.220 --> 00:39:25.890
where we learned lots of
information beyond their names.

00:39:25.890 --> 00:39:29.770
But basically all we then get
is just the name of the scribe

00:39:29.770 --> 00:39:34.040
who then says, I copied it word
for word, letter for letter,

00:39:34.040 --> 00:39:37.010
symbol for symbol, from the
text that was before me.

00:39:37.010 --> 00:39:40.450
So, unfortunately, we can say
nothing beyond that, yeah.

00:39:40.450 --> 00:39:43.250
I should say something
about female authorship.

00:39:43.250 --> 00:39:45.980
Our assumption is that almost
all texts are written by men.

00:39:45.980 --> 00:39:48.790
That's just the working hypothesis
in the Ancient Near East.

00:39:48.790 --> 00:39:51.100
Having said that, and now I'm going
to speak out of the other side

00:39:51.100 --> 00:39:54.770
of my mouth, the earliest
writer whom we know by name

00:39:54.770 --> 00:40:00.570
in the world was a Sumerian
priestess named Enheduanna.

00:40:00.570 --> 00:40:02.660
And she left us some hymns

00:40:02.660 --> 00:40:05.460
to the Goddess Ishtar,
and we know her name.

00:40:05.460 --> 00:40:08.840
And it's very possible that we know
her name because she was a woman

00:40:08.840 --> 00:40:10.910
and felt it was necessary
to give us her name.

00:40:10.910 --> 00:40:12.820
It was around 2000 BCE.

00:40:12.820 --> 00:40:15.410
A little bit actually
-- or 2200 BCE.

00:40:15.410 --> 00:40:16.990
So that would be an exception.

00:40:16.990 --> 00:40:21.450
But it also gives us the idea
that, yes, women did author texts.

00:40:21.450 --> 00:40:24.150
And as far as the authorship
of the "Song of Songs,"

00:40:24.150 --> 00:40:26.340
and I am totally agnostic on this,

00:40:26.340 --> 00:40:30.800
the female authorship has
been proposed by scholars

00:40:30.800 --> 00:40:36.240
and most notably by the great
scholar Shelomo Dov Goitein

00:40:36.240 --> 00:40:40.440
who is associated with his
great work on the Cairo Geniza,

00:40:40.440 --> 00:40:45.030
but also made major contributions
to the study of The Bible as well.

00:40:45.030 --> 00:40:49.620
Who else? Yes, sir.

00:40:49.620 --> 00:40:58.540
&gt;&gt; If I understand you correctly,
you're saying that a text written

00:40:58.540 --> 00:41:01.390
by a woman would be very rare.

00:41:01.390 --> 00:41:08.800
But this brings to mind the <i>The
Book of J </i>by Professor Harold Bloom

00:41:08.800 --> 00:41:13.630
who sets out the hypothesis
that the J text

00:41:13.630 --> 00:41:18.330
and the core is written
by a Negro princess.

00:41:18.330 --> 00:41:19.630
&gt;&gt; Gary Rendsburg: Right.

00:41:19.630 --> 00:41:20.930
&gt;&gt; Would you comment on it?

00:41:20.930 --> 00:41:22.230
&gt;&gt; Gary Rendsburg: I have the
greatest respect for Harold Bloom

00:41:22.230 --> 00:41:25.140
who is just one of the world's
greatest Shakespeare scholars

00:41:25.140 --> 00:41:28.410
and elucidators of Renaissance
English Literature and much else

00:41:28.410 --> 00:41:30.250
in English and world literature.

00:41:30.250 --> 00:41:33.200
But he simply doesn't know the
biblical material well enough,

00:41:33.200 --> 00:41:34.730
I'm sorry, to say.

00:41:34.730 --> 00:41:37.020
Anything is possible.

00:41:37.020 --> 00:41:39.770
First of all, I even reject
the notion of a J source,

00:41:39.770 --> 00:41:42.340
I have to tell you that, because
I approach the biblical material

00:41:42.340 --> 00:41:45.280
differently from the
usual source critics.

00:41:45.280 --> 00:41:52.220
But he is -- this was a
very well-known book of his,

00:41:52.220 --> 00:41:54.520
where it made a big popular
splash when he wrote it.

00:41:54.520 --> 00:41:57.310
And I don't want to say anything
harsh about Professor Bloom

00:41:57.310 --> 00:41:59.020
because I've learned so
much from his writings.

00:41:59.020 --> 00:42:02.100
I was an English major as an
undergraduate and, of course,

00:42:02.100 --> 00:42:03.860
Bloom was something we all read.

00:42:03.860 --> 00:42:06.310
And I continue to read
and learn from his work.

00:42:06.310 --> 00:42:08.730
But his work on biblical
studies should just be set aside

00:42:08.730 --> 00:42:14.830
for the moment, with all due
respect to his remarkable intellect

00:42:14.830 --> 00:42:19.260
and great contributions to the
field of comparative literature.

00:42:19.260 --> 00:42:22.510
Yes. Yes.

00:42:22.510 --> 00:42:47.120
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

00:42:47.120 --> 00:42:48.420
&gt;&gt; Gary Rendsburg: Okay.

00:42:48.420 --> 00:42:53.150
So the question was, at what point
did Jewish authors actually begin

00:42:53.150 --> 00:42:58.230
to ascribe their names
to their compositions?

00:42:58.230 --> 00:43:01.060
The second half of your question
I'll deal with in just a second.

00:43:01.060 --> 00:43:05.920
And the answer to that is, under
the -- in the Age of Hellenism.

00:43:05.920 --> 00:43:10.780
When Alexander the Great
conquered the Near East in 330 BCE,

00:43:10.780 --> 00:43:12.740
Hellenism spread throughout.

00:43:12.740 --> 00:43:14.570
Egypt became Hellenized.

00:43:14.570 --> 00:43:16.310
The Land of Israel
became Hellenized.

00:43:16.310 --> 00:43:18.720
What we now call modern-day
Syria became Hellenized.

00:43:18.720 --> 00:43:22.670
And, actually, far to the
east, as far east as Iran

00:43:22.670 --> 00:43:25.360
and modern-day Afghanistan we
have Greek inscriptions all

00:43:25.360 --> 00:43:28.230
because of the great
empire that Alexander built.

00:43:28.230 --> 00:43:33.080 position:56%
And Hellenistic influence
certainly took hold on those regions

00:43:33.080 --> 00:43:34.590
which were closest to Greece --

00:43:34.590 --> 00:43:37.330
Egypt, the Land of
Israel, Syria, and so on.

00:43:37.330 --> 00:43:42.680
The earliest Jewish writer who left
his name to a book is <i>The Book</i>

00:43:42.680 --> 00:43:45.660
<i>of Ben Sira </i>written in 180 BCE,

00:43:45.660 --> 00:43:47.530
where we actually know
the name of the author.

00:43:47.530 --> 00:43:51.520
Embedded into the Hebrew text
is the name of the author.

00:43:51.520 --> 00:43:54.570
And that Hebrew text, as you
may know, was lost at some point

00:43:54.570 --> 00:43:59.150 position:56%
in the Middle Ages and was recovered
in the Cairo Ganesa in the end

00:43:59.150 --> 00:44:02.090
of the 19th century -- Solomon
Schechter being the first one

00:44:02.090 --> 00:44:06.390 position:56%
to identify a Hebrew original of the
Greek translation of <i>Ben Sira </i>.

00:44:06.390 --> 00:44:08.660
But we have the [inaudible]
in Greek translation

00:44:08.660 --> 00:44:10.980
and we have two-thirds
of it now in Hebrew.

00:44:10.980 --> 00:44:12.280 position:56%
It's Heboriginal [assumed spelling].

00:44:12.280 --> 00:44:14.410
So he would be the
first author to do so.

00:44:14.410 --> 00:44:17.500
And then in his wake you also --
writing in Hebrew I should say.

00:44:17.500 --> 00:44:19.340
He's the first author
writing in Hebrew to do this,

00:44:19.340 --> 00:44:21.090
Jewish author writing in Hebrew.

00:44:21.090 --> 00:44:24.760
There were Jewish authors
in Egypt who actually wrote

00:44:24.760 --> 00:44:27.390 position:56%
in Greek even earlier than Ben Sira.

00:44:27.390 --> 00:44:29.410
We have only snippets
of their material.

00:44:29.410 --> 00:44:32.870
And a century after that
we have the famous case

00:44:32.870 --> 00:44:34.990
of Philo, a prolific writer.

00:44:34.990 --> 00:44:37.790
So, yes, all of these Greek Jewish
writers left us their names,

00:44:37.790 --> 00:44:40.300
and Josephus in that
mode is writing in Greek.

00:44:40.300 --> 00:44:44.250
So he, of course, would give
us his name, as he does.

00:44:44.250 --> 00:44:47.880
Now, the second part of the
question deals with a comment

00:44:47.880 --> 00:44:49.540
in the <i>Talmud </i>in
the "Tractate of" --

00:44:49.540 --> 00:44:53.280
in the <i>Babylonian Talmud </i>in the
"Tractate of Bava Batra" from,

00:44:53.280 --> 00:44:56.070
let's say maybe 4- or 500 CE,

00:44:56.070 --> 00:45:00.340
although that passage is
evoking an earlier layer

00:45:00.340 --> 00:45:02.650
of rabbinic literature, so
it may go back what's known

00:45:02.650 --> 00:45:04.640
as a Brita in Hebrew, or Aramaic.

00:45:04.640 --> 00:45:06.730
It may go back to 200 CE.

00:45:06.730 --> 00:45:09.340
And there the rabbi's
attempt to give us the names

00:45:09.340 --> 00:45:11.740
of who wrote the biblical
books, right?

00:45:11.740 --> 00:45:14.240
So that's what -- they
do that at that point.

00:45:14.240 --> 00:45:16.510
They actually don't mention
the "Torah" in that passage,

00:45:16.510 --> 00:45:18.860
because I guess the
"Torah's" just assumed

00:45:18.860 --> 00:45:21.960
to have Mosaic authorship
or divine word.

00:45:21.960 --> 00:45:24.750
But it starts with Joshua and it
works through, and it attempts

00:45:24.750 --> 00:45:27.740
to give us the who wrote
book this and book that.

00:45:27.740 --> 00:45:30.610
So that is probably, again, part
of the Hellenistic influence

00:45:30.610 --> 00:45:32.790
on the rabbis who now
decided that they needed

00:45:32.790 --> 00:45:35.930
to ascribe the biblical
books to particular authors.

00:45:35.930 --> 00:45:37.990
And if I didn't mention --
I did not mention the "Song

00:45:37.990 --> 00:45:40.160
of Songs" gets attributed
to Solomon,

00:45:40.160 --> 00:45:43.220
which is why it's also known
as the "Song of Solomon" in --

00:45:43.220 --> 00:45:46.020
more likely in Christian context.

00:45:46.020 --> 00:45:47.820
Yes.

00:45:47.820 --> 00:46:01.520
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

00:46:01.520 --> 00:46:04.360
Okay. Who claims this did you say?

00:46:04.360 --> 00:46:05.660
Ethiopes and Christians.

00:46:05.660 --> 00:46:06.960
I though so.

00:46:06.960 --> 00:46:08.660
Right. So the Ethiopes
and Christians --

00:46:08.660 --> 00:46:13.120
I don't know, venerate may
be too great a term for it,

00:46:13.120 --> 00:46:17.310 position:56%
but venerate the story of Solomon
and the visit of the Queen of Sheba,

00:46:17.310 --> 00:46:19.280
Sheba being in far Southern Arabia,

00:46:19.280 --> 00:46:22.660
just across the Red
Sea from Ethiopia.

00:46:22.660 --> 00:46:29.750
And so this would be part of the
Jewish and Christian traditions

00:46:29.750 --> 00:46:34.680
of Solomon writing the <i>Book
of Song of Songs" in his youth.</i>

00:46:34.680 --> 00:46:37.500
<i>And I don't think there
were Jewish passages</i>

00:46:37.500 --> 00:46:40.900
<i>which ascribe it specifically to
the visit of the Queen of Sheba,</i>

00:46:40.900 --> 00:46:42.250
<i>but there are rabbinic texts</i>

00:46:42.250 --> 00:46:45.760
<i>which ascribe Solomon's authorship
during the time of his youth,</i>

00:46:45.760 --> 00:46:48.620
<i>in contrast to his
authorship of the Book</i>

00:46:48.620 --> 00:46:51.280
<i>of Proverbs </i>which he
did in full maturity.

00:46:51.280 --> 00:46:55.850
And then the <i>Book of Ecclesiastes"
or Kohelet </i>which he did in old age.

00:46:55.850 --> 00:46:58.120
So that's as much as
I can say about it.

00:46:58.120 --> 00:46:59.720
So it's a beautiful
tradition, of course,

00:46:59.720 --> 00:47:02.230
amongst the Ethiopian Christians.

00:47:02.230 --> 00:47:03.620
So thanks for reminding us of that.

00:47:03.620 --> 00:47:08.800
And, of course, for the great
place that Solomon holds

00:47:08.800 --> 00:47:11.220
in the Ethiopian tradition.

00:47:11.220 --> 00:47:12.710
Yeah.

